  "articleSummary": "The article argues that well‑designed multiple‑choice questions (MCQs) are a powerful teaching tool, not just a cheap assessment method, because the distractors themselves encode common misconceptions and reveal learners’ mental models. By deliberately crafting wrong answers that reflect real misunderstandings—such as legacy syntax, cross‑platform habits, or edge‑case conditions—an MCQ can teach and diagnose knowledge before any explanation is given, as illustrated with a PostgreSQL identity‑column quiz that serves beginners, intermediates, and experts simultaneously. The piece is aimed at educators, technical writers, and developers who create instructional content or quizzes, and it adopts an analytical, tutorial‑style tone that repeatedly uses the metaphor of “the distractor as the curriculum” to frame its points.",
